  "text": "3.2.4. The q-value procedure. The p-value has a nice interpretation and provides a convenient framework for testing a single hypothesis, e.g. we reject the null if the p-value is less than \u03b1. The q-value [CITATION_1] can be viewed as an analogue of the p-value in the FDR paradigm in the sense that if we want to carry out an FDR analysis at level \u03b1, then we can obtain the q-value for each test and reject Hi if its q-value is less than \u03b1. The q-value has gained great popularity in large-scale \"omics\" research such as genomics and proteomics due to its convenience and nice interpretation. Roughly speaking, the q-value of a test measures the fraction of false discoveries when that test is just rejected. Consider the random mixture model (18), the positive FDR (pFDR) is defined as pFDR(t) = E N 10 R R > 0 = (1 \u2212 n)t/G(t), where t is the p-value cutoff. The q-value of Hi is the smallest FDR level such that Hi can be rejected:",
